<TEXT>
president corazon aquinos gettough 
move against her opponents was widely hailed as a welcome sign of 
strength but a supreme court rebuff and bloodshed in the north 
raise doubts about skill in implementing the policy 
last week the government filed rebellion with murder charges 
against opposition sen juan ponce enrile and six others in 
connection with the failed dec 19 coup in which 113 people were 
killed 
the filing of charges was widely praised by commentators and the 
media who recalled the generally mild treatment of conspirators 
after some of the five previous coup attempts since mrs aquino 
took office 
its a welcome sign said one western diplomat speaking 
last week on condition of anonymity its about time she showed 
toughness the top priority for this government now is survival 
but in recent days the strategy shows signs of unraveling 
because of tactical blunders 
at issue was a decision to indict enrile and the others for 
rebellion with murder a charge used by the late president 
ferdinand marcos but which mrs aquino nullified in 1987 as 
repressive 
simple rebellion is punishable by six to 12 years imprisonment 
and defendants are normally allowed bail rebellion with murder 
however provides a life sentence with no bail that would keep 
enrile and the others in detention even before the trial began 
on tuesday however the supreme court released enrile and two 
fellow defendants on bail and a justice said the tribunal would 
decide later on the validity of the dual charge 
presidential press secretary tomas gomez today said the ruling 
is neither a setback for the government nor is it a victory for 
enrile because the main topic has not been decided the validity 
of the charge 
but during his week in custody enrile held frequent news 
conferences where he sought to portray himself as an aggrieved 
underdog he often told reporters he was praying for mrs aquino 
whom he helped sweep to power in 1986 and thanked her for the 
free publicity 
sen ernesto maceda a lawyer and frequent administration 
critic said the government had tranformed enrile into a martyr 
and a hero 
before leaving the police headquarters where he was held enrile 
signed autographs for his jailers they cheered when he told them 
if you need anything just come to my office 
whoever was responsible for the misguided advice and ensuing 
fiasco should perhaps consider offering their resignations 
said the manila times an independent daily 
compounding the problem is the public perception that evidence 
against enrile is weak in the charge sheet the government based 
its case is based on statements by three waiters who claimed they 
saw a coup leader former lt col gregorio gringo honasan at 
enriles home on the first day of the december coup attempt 
enriles lawyer renato cayetano claims he has 53 witnesses 
ready to testify that honasan was not there the waiters did not 
testify about any alleged conversations between enrile and honasan 
according to documents made public 
we can only hope the government has sufficient evidence to 
back up the charges said the independent philippine daily 
inquirer otherwise it would lend credence to the enrile camps 
accusations that the senator was held on a spurious charge as part 
of a grand political vendetta 
the decision to indict the seven on the controversial dual 
charge may also have contributed to sundays bloodshed in 
tuguegarao 250 miles north of manila 
officials went to tuguegarao capital of cagayan province to 
arrest suspended provincial gov rodolfo aguinaldo one of the 
seven defendants aguinaldo told reporters he was willing to 
surrender on rebellion charges but not murder because i didnt 
kill anybody 
after four days of negotiations aguinaldos followers seized a 
hotel taking brig gen oscar florendo prisoner and trapping local 
governments secretary luis santos on the second floor 
florendo was killed when government troops recaptured the hotel 
aguinaldo escaped with an estimated 200 armed followers mrs 
aquino says florendo was murdered by aguinaldos forces 
most lawyers believe that the situation in cagayan would never 
have ended in bloodshed if government prosecutors had not 
reinvented the charge of rebellion complexed with murder wrote 
commentator luis beltran in the manila standard was it worth the 
price just to show decisiveness and firmness 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
robert reid has been ap chief of bureau in 
manila since september 1986 
