<TEXT>
the us postal service is beginning steps to 
raise prices even while conceding that the new rates may be too 
much too soon 
more expensive postage including a 30cent first class stamp 
is still nearly a year away thanks to a lengthy and complex 
ratemaking process established by congress 
the mail agency is facing a deficit of between 14 billion and 
16 billion in this fiscal year forcing it to begin the effort to 
raise revenue it is required by law to break even over time and no 
longer receives any taxpayer subsidy 
i think it should have been 28 or 29 cents and we want to pay 
that back to the american people we want to improve service and 
operate below the rate of inflation we want that to be translated 
into never again saying too much too soon postmaster general 
anthony m frank said tuesday 
we cannot ignore that increases in postal costs do occur just 
as they do in any business said robert setrakian chairman of 
the postal services board of governors which proposed the rate 
hikes 
setrakian estimated that the higher rates would cost the average 
individual 10 to 11 annually 
frank said the rate increase is more than the inflation that has 
occurred since the current prices took effect in 1988 because of 
unexpectedly high costs 
productivity although improving recently didnt increase as 
fast as expected he said in addition costs were considerably 
higher than planned including employee health costs and the 
requirement that the postal service contribute funds to help defray 
the federal budget deficit in recent years 
those factors forced the agency to seek a 19 percent rate 
increase to cover a period when inflation is projected to total 
about 14 percent frank said 
opposition to higher prices came immediately from diverse 
directions 
the new york state consumer protection board announced that it 
will intervene in the rate case to oppose the plan 
it is ludicrous to ask consumers to pay more for slower mail 
service said richard m kessel the commissions executive 
director 
the proposed increase is excessive and selfdefeating the 
american bankers association argued 
such postal rate increases imposed upon business ultimately 
in some fashion will be paid by busness customers said vincent 
a liguori chairman of abas postal service committee 
the people are going to have to save the post office from 
itself said consumer advocate ralph nader who proposed to set 
up a grassroots organization of mail users 
the planned rate hike is unreasonable and unjustified 
charged tracey schreft of the us chamber of commerce 
and robert kamerschen head of advo system inc the nations 
largest advertising mailer said he is concerned that raising rates 
will drive profitable mail out of the postal system just at the 
time its needed most 
the vote tuesday by the postal board of governors was just the 
first step in the process the question now goes to the independent 
postal rate commission 
the fivemember commission has 10 months to consider the case 
it will hold hearings and solicit information from the postal 
service businesses and individuals 
following that the commission will send a set of proposed rates 
back to the postal governors often it agrees with the original 
request but not always 
in 1984 for example the postal service proposed a 23cent 
first class rate the postal rate commission cut that back to 22 
cents the governors accepted that decision 
but they dont have to if the governors can put together a 
unanimous vote they can overrule the commission that happened in 
1981 when the governors raised the firstclass rate from 15 cents 
to 20 cents even though the commission said 18 cents would be 
enough 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

