<TEXT>
the new rates proposed by the board of 
governors of the us postal service would mean higher mail costs 
for most individuals and businesses 
here are some examples of the changes when the new rates take 
effect probably sometime in early 1991 
individual cost of mailing a letter or paying a bill 30 cents 
up from 25 cents 
cost to mail a regular post card 20 cents up from 15 cents 
price of sending a sevenpound package 506 up from 400 
charge to a bank to send a threeounce statement 76 cents up 
from 65 cents 
department store cost to mail a presorted bill 26 cents up 
from 21 cents 
price to send a creditcard bill sorted according to the full 
ninedigit zip code 253 cents up from 205 cents 
utility company cost to send a bill with imprinted bar code 
allowing it to be handled by machines 243 cents up from 20 cents 
lawyers cost to send onepound of legal documents by priority 
mail 275 up from 240 
charge to send eight ounces of highspeed business information 
via express mail 975 up from 875 
cost for twopounds of urgent business materials via express 
mail 1375 up from 1200 
postage for a typical weekly newsmagazine 16 cents up from 
135 cents 
cost of sending a somewhat heavier monthly magazine 374 
cents up from 297 cents 
postage for two ounces of advertising with special bar code 
imprinted to permit handling by new automated machinery 161 
cents down from 167 cents 
rate for halfpound catalog sorted according to zip code 331 
cents up from 271 cents 
charge for advertising mail sorted in advance according to the 
sequence of houses that the letter carrier visits 96 cents down 
from 101 cents 
cost of sending a local threepound business package 200 up 
from 158 
book club cost to mail a fourpound package 226 up from 
195 
