<TEXT>
east german workers have won the right to 
strike for the first time in their countrys 40year history under 
a new labor law that also prohibits employers from locking out 
workers 
the law overwhelming approved tuesday by parliament comes as 
the country lurches ever closer to reunification with west germany 
legislators praised the new labor code for its mixing of 
marketstyle reforms with traditional socialist protections but 
they conceded that it probably would be objectionable to west 
german investors and employers 
the law easily won approval from the 385 lawmakers present for 
what is expected to be the last session of the 500member peoples 
chamber before the countrys first competitive elections on march 
18 only six voted against the measure with 53 abstentions debate 
was minimal 
the future of the new law may rest with the new 400member 
parliament many labor principles embodied in the law require 
implementing legislation that will have to be tackled after the new 
legislative body is seated 
the strike clause however is among changes to take effect next 
week 
lawmakers hailed the nolockout clause as a workers right not 
enjoyed in west germany 
because the law is likely to be seen as imbalanced by west 
german industries seeking to build plants or engage in joint 
production operations in east germany it may serve to slow the 
investment considered essential to turning around the flagging 
economy 
the law comes in the form of a constitutional change it permits 
unions to call strikes if arbitration fails to resolve 
labormanagement differences in negotiations 
strikes have been forbidden in east germany and most other 
formerly socialist states with labor unions traditionally 
powerless to challenge the communists who ruled until democratic 
upheavals toppled them last year 
the government now will have the right to intercede and stop a 
strike only if the walkout is deemed a threat to public order 
the law provides that no one can reduce or hinder unions in 
their rightful occupation 
communist lawmaker kaethe niederkirchner said such a broad 
protection was likely to disturb the capitalists next door he 
quoted west german employers association president klaus murmann as 
describing the law as a hindrance to intergerman economic 
cooperation 
parliament also adopted additional measures on election 
procedures including extending voting rights to foreigners who 
have lived in east germany for two years or more 
the changes are the latest since a popular uprising forced 
communist hardliner erich honecker to step down in october the 
opening of the berlin wall a month later and the introduction of 
noncommunists and opposition democratic reformers into the interim 
government 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

