thousands of haitianamericans protested the new 
federal ban on blood donations by haitians saying the aids 
prevention policy would increase discrimination against them 
after the rally by about 8000 people tuesday the food and drug 
administration responded by promising to consult with 
haitianamericans and convene a public meeting of its blood 
products advisory committee to discuss the issue 
the haitian immigrants gathered in a dusty field across from fda 
offices here chanting fda racists waving redandblue 
haitian flags and carrying signs saying fda bigots must go 
police arrested three people when the crowd surged onto fda 
property 
anyone can die from aids from the president to the poorest 
man i dont see why they blame the haitians said jean francois 
a college student 
the policy announced last month is designed to help keep 
aidstainted blood out of the nations supply by requiring blood 
banks to refuse donations from people who were born in or who 
emigrated from haiti and subsaharan africa 
protesters claim the policy unfairly lumps them with the other 
groups discouraged from giving blood intravenous drug users 
homosexuals and prostitutes 
this is an acquired disease its behavioral said philomena 
jadotte 24 a nursing student who emigrated from haiti 10 years 
ago there are more hispanics dying of aids in miami than 
haitians why are we being singled out because were black 
many haitians already feel unwanted in south florida because of 
us immigration policy that welcomes cuban and nicaraguan emigres 
but returns most haitians to their impoverished violent homeland 
a previous ban permitted blood donations from haitians and 
subsaharan africans only if they emigrated before 1977 but the 
fda changed its policy after research cast doubt on the reliability 
of that date as an indicator of when the disease began to spread 
outside the united states said fda spokesman brad stone 
unlike other groups most haitians who have aids got the fatal 
disease through heterosexual transmission and stone said theres 
no good way to screen potential carriers from the rest of the 
haitian population 
