have been stored in this country for more than 20 years 
in may 1986 thenpresident reagan and chancellor helmut kohl 
agreed that all the artillery shells would be removed 
the presence of chemical weapons on german soil has long been 
criticized by west german environmentalists and peace activists 
they have alleged that in case of an accident involving chemical 
weapons us security concerns would take precedence over the 
protection of west germans 
us officials have strongly denied the claim 
speaking to reporters stoltenberg insisted the transport which 
is expected to take about three months would present no dangers to 
the environment or the public but he asked west germans to help 
make sure there are no attempts at disruption of the shipments 
stoltenberg did not specify what kinds of disruptions 
concerned him 
us army gen john heldstab deputy chief of staff for 
operations for the us armyeurope told reporters the army was 
confident that proper security would be provided for the 
transports 
stoltenberg said withdrawal of the artillery shells is scheduled 
to begin in july and last until september 
he said the shells now kept at a depot near clausen in the 
state of rhinelandpalatinate would be loaded into thick 
airtight steel magazines which would in turn be placed inside 
specially designed sheetmetal containers 
it was apparently the first official statement indicating where 
the chemical weapons are kept their location had previously been 
kept top secret for security reasons 
stoltenberg said the containers would be transported by truck to 
a us munitions depot in miesau 25 miles from clausen and loaded 
aboard railway cars the trains would transport the containers to 
the north sea port of nordenham where they will be loaded aboard 
specially equipped us transport ships stoltenberg said the 
munitions will then be shipped to the johnston atoll in the pacific 
for destruction 
he also said the strictest security conditions would be used 
for the transport of the artillery shells including special 
training for truck drivers moving the containers out of clausen 
col eckart fischer of the west german army said the artillery 
shells contain about 400 tons of the nerve gases vx and 
sarin 
fischer told reporters that more than 5000 containers will be 
needed to move the 155mm and 203mm artillery shells 
heldstab said the munitions represented about 1 percent of the 
united states total stockpile of chemical weapons 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

