<TEXT>
universities found to be weak in ideological or 
political studies will have their enrollments cut and may be shut 
down chinas leading daily said wednesday 
the official peoples daily said the state education commission 
also decided to reduce enrollments of universities with graduates 
in majors in less demand when job assignments are made most likely 
to be affected are programs in the liberal arts 
the commission meeting in the southern city of changsha worked 
out an enrollment plan for 620000 new undergraduates and 
vocational students for the school year starting in the fall 
in 1989 colleges and universities enrolled 597000 freshmen a 
sharp drop of 108 percent from 1988 as the government moved to 
purify campuses of bourgeois liberal tendencies 
many universities where students actively participated in the 
apriljune prodemocracy movement had their freshman classes cut 
beijing university chinas most prestigious campus and a center 
of the democracy campaign crushed by military force on june 34 
had its freshman enrollment slashed from 2100 to 800 with all 
firstyear students sent out of beijing for a year at a military 
school 
ideological studies emphasizing loyalty to the communist party 
were expanded and made compulsory and workstudy programs designed 
to make students more in touch with the masses were increased 
the education commission said enrollments will be cut or 
suspended in 1990 for schools weak in political and ideological 
work and where courses are not clearly linked to future jobs 
it said experiments in allowing a few students to pay their own 
way would continue but that selffinanced students would be 
restricted to less than 3 percent of the total 
the government previously promoted the idea of accepting more 
students who pay their own tuition as a means of raising funds for 
the woefully underfinanced education system selfpaid students 
were accepted with lower test scores and given greater freedom to 
choose their own jobs after graduation 
the drive to ensure the ideological loyalty of students 
however appears to have made financially independent students 
suspect normally almost all tuition and boarding costs are 
subsidized by the government 
the peoples daily in a separate article reported a public 
security ministry crackdown on students who pay large sums to 
obtain admission documents from foreign schools 
it said the ministry which must approve all passports wont 
recognize illegally bought admission notices or economic guarantee 
documents and that anyone caught practicing fraud or illegally 
dealing in foreign exchange will have their passports seized 
a small number of foreign organizations and individuals have 
cheated chinese and made large profits by selling admissions to 
foreign schools it said 
the government has already moved to discourage the many students 
wanting to study in the west by making it more difficult to obtain 
transcripts and take englishlanguage proficiency tests and 
requiring applicants to have up to five years work experience 
before going abroad 
