<TEXT>
american workers productivity in the nonfarm 
portion of the nations economy last year posted its worst 
performance since 1982 improving only 09 percent the government 
said wednesday 
meanwhile hourly labor costs a major inflation measure for 
businesses escalated significantly jumping by 54 percent the 
labor department said that increase up from 47 percent in 1988 
was the biggest rise in hourly labor costs since the 198182 
recession 
thats what happens when you have a slowdown in the economy 
you get squeezed from both ends the two blades of the scissors 
subdued productivity and higher labor costs began to push 
together said robert dederick chief economist for the northern 
trust co of chicago 
there is no real evidence that productivity is going to 
escalate any time soon were not likely to break out of this vice 
in 1990 dederick said 
the 09 percent productivity gain for the year was the same 
improvement reported in preliminary figures provided last month as 
was the 02 percent productivity gain reported for the 
octoberdecember period 
the labor department said the 09 percent increase in 
productivity defined as output per hour of work was less than 
half the 2 percent gain recorded in 1988 
the fourth quarters productivity gain of 02 percent was well 
below the 24 percent gain of the previous quarter 
since the end of the 198182 recession productivity growth has 
averaged 18 percent a year while a slight improvement over the 
12 percent average growth in the 1970s it was still far below the 
33 percent rate of increase posted in the two decades after world 
war ii when american workers enjoyed healthy wage gains and a 
rising standard of living 
increasing productivity is considered basic to boosting living 
standards because it allows businesses to pay workers more as their 
output rises without risking higher inflation 
in addition to the large increase in hourly compensation the 
report showed that unit labor costs another key determinant of 
future price inflation shot up 45 percent for the year compared 
with a 27 percent increase in 1988 unit labor costs reflect 
changes in compensation as well as changes in productivity 
hourly labor costs for the fourth quarter increased by 6 
percent the department said 
output in the nonfarm portion was up 33 percent in 1989 while 
the number of hours worked rose by 24 percent giving the 09 
percent increase in productivity 
for the fourth quarter output was unchanged and the number of 
hours worked fell by 02 percent the first drop since 1986 
in the manufacturing sector productivity grew by 28 percent 
for both the year and the quarter during the octoberdecember 
period productivity in the manufacturing of nondurable goods 
increased by 83 percent to outweigh the 04 percent productivity 
decline in durable goods the report said 
