<TEXT>
chiang wego the sole surviving son of 
generalissimo chiang kaishek has emerged as a wild card in the 
upcoming presidential election as his fathers aging cronies dream 
of reestablishing the family dynasty 
gen chiang is still highly respected by our mainland 
compatriots said teng chieh a prominent member of the electoral 
college that will chose a new president march 21 
the attention focusing on chiang wego a 73yearold retired 
general has come quickly after a career spent in the shadow of his 
father and elder brother chiang chingkuo who together led the 
nationalist chinese government for six decades first in china and 
then in taiwan 
his political star did not rise measurably when his brother died 
in 1988 and was succeeded by his handpicked vice president lee 
tenghui 
but president lee is shakily approaching his first major 
political test in which he must win the approval of the 752seat 
national assembly or electoral college to secure a sixyear term 
although lee already has received the ruling nationalist party 
endorsement the assembly is dominated by aging politicians who 
escaped to taiwan with chiang kaishek in 1949 after losing a civil 
war to the communists they still dream of returning victoriously 
to the chinese mainland 
the old guard assemblyman have not faced election since arriving 
in taiwan and have been frozen in office to support the nationalist 
claim to still be the legitimate government of all china 
while chiang wego shares their dream of returning to the 
mainland lee is a pragmatic taiwanborn politician more concerned 
with ruling this island of 20 million people 
about 200 assemblymen have defied lees choice of a top aide as 
running mate by openly supporting chiang for vice president many 
of them actually want chiang to be president but realize that a 
taiwanese must fill the top slot for political reasons 
chiang has responded by saying he would not actively seek the 
presidency or vice presidency but he added that there is nothing 
i can do to control the assemblymen he has refused to rule out 
accepting either position 
he also has accused media of misinterpreting remarks made in 
1985 by his brother who said if someone asks me whether anyone 
in my family would run for the next presidential term my reply is 
it cant be and it wont be 
the statement was widely viewed as referring to all relatives 
but chiang wego has claimed his brother was only referring to his 
sons 
lee is taking the challenge seriously and has scrambled to meet 
with assemblymen to shore up support the power struggle has 
stirred up the most serious political crisis in 40 years said 
lu yali history professor at national taiwan university 
among chiangs critics is the liberal weekly magazine 
journalist which said in an editorial that his activities exposed 
his backward thoughts muddled head unrestrained mind and weak 
will 
