birmingham ala mayor richard arrington 
urged senators wednesday to approve a new civil rights bill and 
help his city end 16 years of costly litigation over its hiring and 
promotion practices 
arrington told the senate labor and human resources committee 
the terrible financial burden on the city from the court battle 
will continue indefinitely unless congress overturns a supreme 
court decision last year on affirmative action 
the supreme court ruled white birmingham firefighters may 
challenge a courtapproved 1981 agreement between the city the 
justice department and black workers giving preferential treatment 
to minorities and women in city jobs 
the proposed civil rights act of 1990 would overturn that ruling 
by permitting workers to challenge employment practices from court 
orders or consent decress only if they did not know about or were 
denied a chance to challenge the orders beforehand 
we are not here seeking a license to engage in unlawful 
reverse discrimination arrington testified we are not here 
seeking to gag the objections legitimate or otherwise of white 
employees to affirmative action 
but raymond p fitzpatrick jr attorney for the white 
firefighters told the committee congress should let the ruling 
stand saying the court had reaffirmed the fundamental 
principle that all americans are entitled to a day in court when 
they believed they have been wronged 
fitzpatrick hinted any legislation to reverse the court ruling 
would lead to another prolonged legal battle over its 
constitutionality 
he said the 1981 agreement approved by a federal judge has 
never been reviewed by an appeals court the city has spent nine 
years trying to block a court from reviewing its decree he said 
arrington said the new bill would guarantee everyone in hiring 
bias disputes the right to a day in court but would still allow 
cities and other employers the right to finality in litigation 
