<TEXT>
life in cooper is just the way its 
residents like it they know each other by name and people smile 
when they speak to strangers at millers corner drugstore high 
school football dominates the conversation and the milkshakes are 
homemade 
but one constant dependable part of that life has abruptly come 
unglued greyhound is on strike and cooper is one of 9000 
communities where the companys buses provide the only intercity 
transportation 
ive only sold one ticket since the strike started and that 
person knew about the strike and wound up hitching a ride to 
dallas said marion miller who runs the family drugstore with 
his father manton 
actually its a good thing he didnt wait around because the 
bus was an hour and a half late said the younger miller whose 
store doubles as the bus station in this town of 2315 people 80 
miles northeast of dallas 
greyhound lines inc americas only nationwide bus system has 
been limping along since its 6300 drivers and about 3000 office 
and maintenance workers went on strike the union which walked out 
friday over wage and job security issues has asked for new talks 
but none are scheduled 
the company has been operating a reduced schedule during the 
6dayold strike using about 700 replacement drivers plus union 
members who cross picket lines greyhound said wednesday its 
ridership tuesday was 371 percent of the same day last year an 
increase from monday 338 percent and fridays 30 percent 
but bus travel in small towns such as cooper has slowed to a 
virtual crawl 
in a small town its more of a sporadic stream of business 
the younger miller said i might have five or six people in a day 
trying to catch a bus but then on other days i might not have 
any 
manton miller said he normally sells about 10 tickets a week 
greyhound pays him 75 a week to serve as agent but some of his 
regular customers are business people who regularly use the bus to 
ship and receive supplies ranging from auto parts to bull semen 
it would be kind of hard for farmers and breeders to schedule 
the semen shipments for their artificial breeding that stuff has 
to be refrigerated and i dont think it can stand to be left around 
for more than two or three days he said 
before the strike four buses passed through cooper daily on the 
route between texarkana and dallas but this week manton miller 
said no buses stopped by his store 
he said the limited bus service resulting from the strike 
reminds him of a time about two years ago when a woman told him 
that it took a rookie bus driver more than 90 minutes to make the 
20mile trip from the town of paris 
thats the kind of problems they have when theyre training 
these new drivers he said when youve got to fill in your 
schedule with all new people youre just asking for problems 
since delta county has evolved from an economy driven by 
agriculture to one struggling to fuel itself by light industry a 
prolonged strike could cripple local businesses that depend on 
greyhounds freight service 
well its going to hurt us said bonnie oats who runs a 
clothing manufacturing plant with her husband zane 
mrs oats said they often receive up to three supply shipments a 
week and the convenience provided by the bus schedules is 
invaluable she said 
we can depend on the bus you dont ever know when ups is 
going to get here she said 
