<TEXT>
requiring all job seekers to show an identity 
card would greatly help enforcement of laws barring the employment 
of illegal aliens the nations chief immigration official said 
wednesday 
gene mcnary who heads the immigration and naturalization 
service told reporters he was not proposing a nationwide identitiy 
card but would consider the concept if it were advanced by others 
i believe it would greatly enhance our ability to enforce 
employer sanctions that prohibit businesses from hiring illegal 
aliens mcnary said 
im not taking the initiative its something that should be 
reviewed and discussed mcnary said i think its up to some 
others its going to take a law passed by congress 
before endorsing the concept id like to have the benefit of 
discussion id like to get the viewpoint of some of the interest 
groups he said 
an identity card would also eliminate the use of fake documents 
by illegal aliens to forge false identities the ins chief said 
under the concept an identity care would be issued to all 
adults seeking work both citizens and aliens with permission from 
ins to hold jobs in this country 
those issued the card would have to show it only to prospective 
employers 
under the 1986 immigration reform and control act employers can 
be fined or prosecuted for employing illegal aliens the provision 
has resulted in complaints that employers have discriminated 
against people they feared were illegal aliens 
studies in california and new york recently blamed the 1986 
laws employer sanctions for discrimination against hispanics and 
members of other ethnic groups who were wrongly suspected of being 
illegal aliens 
the law also bars such discrimination and a justice department 
unit set up in 1987 to handle such cases has received more than 800 
complaints from citizens 
mcnary said he believed the congressional general accounting 
office would discuss the feasibility of issuing a uniform identity 
card in a report it is preparing on the immigration service 
mcnary said he did not know whether the gao would endorse the 
concept which has been discussed by a growing number of lawmakers 
as a way to tighten immigration laws 
many of the discrimination complaints against employers arise 
from confusion about what types of documentation should be required 
for job seekers said andrew strojny the justice departments 
acting special counsel for immigationrelated unfair employment 
practices 
many of the complaints deal with employers not understanding 
what documents are acceptable as proof that a person is a citizen 
or has ins permission to get a job he said 
strojny said that a nationwide identity card would result in 
less discrimination but that personally he feared it would lead 
to a system under which the government would be granting citizens 
permission to work 
