<TEXT>
nine western european nations 
agreed wednesday on a plan to clean up the north sea one of the 
worlds most polluted salt water bodies 
the nations agreed to reduce by 70 percent their emissions of 
mercury lead cadmium and dioxin which they described as among 
the most dangerous materials polluting the sea 
the reductions are to be achieved by the end of 1995 said dutch 
transport minister hanja maijweggen chairman of a conference on 
cleaning up the north sea 
levels of 37 other toxic materials would be cut in half by the 
same date and polychlorinated biphenyls or pcbs would be phased 
out by 1999 he said 
the 228000squaremile north sea is surrounded by western 
europes most heavily industrialized nations 
pollution from smokestack emissions sea dumping and rivers used 
as industrial sewers have threatened fish and seal populations with 
toxic chemicals 
each year industrial emissions cause some 45 tons of mercury 
3500 tons of lead and 95 tons of cadmium to accumulate into the 
north sea a figure for dioxins was not immediately available 
agreement to limit the materials was a breakthrough for the 
conference as the meeting got underway several nations criticized 
britain which environmental activists here called the dirty man 
of europe 
but maijweggen said that during discussions wednesday britain 
had been very constructive i think that the criticism 
against it has helped a little bit 
in a letter to british environment secretary chris patten 
norway sweden and denmark had expressed dissatisfaction with 
londons announcement this week that it planned to phase out 
industrial waste dumping by late 1992 or early 1993 
we are of the opinion that this should take place without 
further delay the said the letter a copy of which was obtained 
by the associated press 
participating nations at a conference in 1987 in london pledged 
to halt all industrial waste dumping by jan 1 1990 and all north 
sea countries except for britain have met the deadline 
the conference is the third in a series that began in the west 
german port city of bremen in 1984 
the netherlands sweden denmark norway west germany belgium 
france britain and switzerland as well as the european 
commission the eecs executive body are participating ten other 
european nations including east germany and czechoslovakia have 
observer status 
britain announced this week it would end dumping industrial 
waste in two or three years time meantime it would allow annual 
dumpings of 205000270000 tons 
before the conference dutch transport minister hanja 
maijweggen said the british announcement on waste dumping was 
too little and too late 
patten said landbased means of disposal have not yet been 
established for the types of waste that will be dumped in the 
north sea in the coming years 
but critics said the british business world burdened by aging 
industries is balking at the cost of converting to landbased 
waste treatment 
another contentious subject at the conference was marine 
pollution by pcbs believed to be among the most hazardous 
substances manufactured 
annually 39 tons of pcbs find their way into the north sea 
where they are a serious threat to the reproductive cycle of seals 
seal populations in the area are rapidly dwindling 
patten said that contrary to the opinion of the other states 
it is essential to link phaseout with destruction he said 
longterm storage of pcbs is environmentally unacceptable 
west germany is strongly pushing for a total ban on the use of 
pcbs by 1995 under that proposal pcbs now in use for instance 
as coolants in heavyduty electrical equipment should be stored 
until environmentally safe technology has been develop to destroy 
them 
