americans took out 354 billion more in 
consumer credit than they retired in january as they flocked to 
auto dealerships to lock in on newly reinstated sales incentives 
the federal reserve said wednesday 
the fed said overall consumer credit advanced at a seasonally 
adjusted annual rate of 59 percent following a 73 percent gain in 
december when holiday shopping was at its peak consumer credit 
includes all consumer loans except mortgages 
credit card debt slowed to a 14 percent gain at an annual rate 
after rising 237 percent during the december holiday shopping 
period 
revolving or credit card credit rose just 243 million in 
january compared to a 394 billion advance in december it was 
the lowest increase since a 904 million advance in september 
except for auto sales sluggish consumer buying as the new year 
began also was reflected in last weeks commerce department report 
which showed that personal consumption spending slowed from a 1 
percent gain in december to a 06 percent increase in january 
automobile credit on the other hand jumped a seasonally 
adjusted 186 billion 77 percent at an annual rate after 
falling 04 percent in december before rebates and lower interest 
rates kicked in 
bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate were up 
145 billion a sharp 86 percent advance after a 3 percent gain 
in december 
but outstanding mobile home debt fell 18 million a 09 percent 
drop and the fourth consecutive monthly decline 
mobile home debt in december was revised wedensday to a 09 
percent decrease from the previously reported 19 percent increase 
that meant that mobile home debt fell in 11 of the last 12 months 
septembers 28 percent gain was the exception 
the various changes left total consumer debt at the end of 
january at 7201 billion 
