<TEXT>
one of 13 defendants in the cult 
slayings of a family of five was allowed to plead guilty wednesday 
to five reduced counts of murder in return for his promise to 
testify for the prosecution 
richard e brand 26 of independence mo was the first to 
plead guilty in the shooting deaths of a couple and their three 
daughters who also were members of the cult 
he had been charged with five counts of aggravated murder and 
five counts of kidnapping and could have faced the death penalty 
if convicted 
the prosecution says brand led the victims into a barn at the 
cults farm in nearby kirtland in northeast ohio bound them with 
tape and watched as four of the five were shot 
the bodies of dennis avery 49 his wife cheryl 42 and their 
children trina 15 rebecca 13 and karen 7 were unearthed 
from a common grave in the barn jan 34 
brand told lake county common pleas judge james w jackson that 
he helped cover up the bodies 
brand told jackson that cult leader jeffrey lundgren recruited 
him to help with the slayings and said he considered lundgren a 
prophet of god 
he informed me i would be helping him in the killings said 
brand standing before the judge in blue jail coveralls and leg 
irons 
the plea could result in a sentence of 75 years to life for 
brand who would serve at least 20 years said prosecutor steven 
latourette 
justice is served because obviously we now have a valuable 
witness latourette said 
the prosecutor said plea bargains with other defendants were 
possible 
brand pleaded guilty to five counts of murder in return for 
prosecutors agreeing to drop the aggravated murder and kidnapping 
counts latourette said his office would agree to seek dismissal of 
those counts if brand cooperates as promised 
latourette has said the family was killed as part of a 
cleansing sacrifice before the cult left the kirtland farm for 
wilderness treks in west virginia and missouri 
lundgren is a defrocked lay minister of the reorganized church 
of jesus christ of latter day saints the church is separate from 
the salt lake citybased church of jesus christ of latterday 
saints known as the mormons although they share beliefs 
lundgren had been a tour guide at the kirtland temple 
four members including lundgren and his 19yearold son damon 
lundgren were arrested in san diego they are fighting extradition 
the rest have been brought to painesville to face charges that 
include aggravated murder kidnapping conspiracy and complicity 
brand who was facing extradition proceedings agreed feb 5 to 
return to ohio from kansas city mo to face charges 
prosecutors said brand was known to fellow cult members by the 
code name talon1 he worked for two years for the nearby city 
of mentor as a sewer and drainage inspector 
