<TEXT>
two participants in the legal fight to 
open the files of a defunct state segregation agency want a federal 
appeals court to order the records edited to protect the privacy of 
people listed in the files 
john salter jr of grand forks nd and the rev edwin king of 
jackson made thet request in a brief filed in the 5th us circuit 
court of appeals in new orleans 
they contend peoples reputations would be unnecessarily damaged 
if the records of the defunct mississippi sovereignty commission 
are opened without editing 
the unrestricted release of the documents will destroy privacy 
rights of hundreds of citizens and will severely aggravate the 
harm already suffered as a result of the commissions illegal 
spying and disruptive activities they said in the brief filed 
recently by new york city attorney david goldstein 
salter is a former tougaloo college professor and king was 
chaplain there during the 1960s the commission spied on both men 
who were heavily involved in the civil rights struggle 
the commission was established in 1956 to fight integration 
gov bill waller vetoed funding for the agency in 1973 and the 
1977 legislature sealed the files until 2027 citing the need to 
protect the privacy of people named in the documents 
us district judge william h barbour jr on july 27 ordered 
the agencys files unsealed but delayed opening them pending the 
appeal by king and salter who were among the plaintiffs who sued 
to open the files 
king and salters appeal seeks to keep private the names of 
victims and of those who unknowingly aided the commission 
plaintiffs who are seeking to open the files maintain however 
that the effort is a subterfuge to protect certain unidentified 
people 
king and salter oppose the release of information they describe 
as private saying the commission made claims of homosexuality 
drug use or communist affiliations against civil rights activists 
in his ruling barbour said victims of commission skulduggery 
could read the records before they were opened and supply any 
desired response or rebuttal which would be made part of the 
permanent files 
the judge has made it clear he believes state law as it exists 
protects those privacy rights and we find that reasonable said 
ken lawrence one of the plaintiffs we would have accepted more 
restrictions but none of the sort king and salter are suggesting 
</TEXT>
