the government moved closer to changing its 
management of alaskas huge tongass national forest on wednesday 
when a senate committee voted unanimously to modify contracts with 
two timber companies 
the bill approved by senate energy and natural resources 
committee also calls for increased environmental protections but 
does not go as far as the measure already passed by the house 
that bill has tougher environmental provisions and would cancel 
rather than modify the 50year contracts the government has with 
alaska pulp co and louisiana pacificketchikan 
who would have predicted we would end up with a unanimous 190 
vote on such a contentious vote as tongass said sen frank 
murkowski ralaska who has worked to preserve the timber 
industrys position in the forest 
approval of the bill by the full senate would send it to a 
conference committee to work out differences with the house 
version both chambers would then have to vote on the final product 
environmentalists interested in preserving wilderness areas have 
focused on the forest which is bigger than some states 
but people in the five or so cities or communities that base 
their economy on the forests timber dont want the changes said 
some wrangell alaska residents who were on hand for the committee 
action they said changes will cost the region jobs 
the representatives of alaska women in timber said congress was 
reneging on its promise to the two companies and at least one of 
the companies would leave the area if the bill passed 
when you invest so much of your life in an area congress 
shouldnt dictate were going to make some changes so you are 
going to have to move said wilma leslie who operates an 
independent treecutting company with her husband 
but critics charge the companies have monopolized timber and 
violated antitrust and labor laws supporters of the house version 
say canceling the 50year sweetheart deals would open the area to 
competition from other firms 
provisions in the senate bill would 
delete from the law the 40 million appropriation that goes to 
tongass for roadbuilding and other timber sale preparation 
activities 
end the requirement that the forest service provide for sale 
45 billion board feet of tongass timber each decade instead the 
service would be obligated to seek to meet market demand for 
timber 
protect hundreds of thousands more acres of land in the 167 
millionacre forest from logging 
create buffer zones around certain streams to protect fisheries 
the contract modifications would make the deals with the two 
companies conform with independent national forest timber sales and 
strengthen forest service management of the tongass 
