<TEXT>
withdrawals from savings institutions 
accelerated in december bringing outflows for all of 1989 to a 
record 736 billion the government said wednesday 
the industry lost 86 billion in deposits excluding interest 
credited in december the office of thrift supervision said that 
was the biggest onemonth drain since a 88 billion outflow in 
september and the 18th in 19 months withdrawals totaled 48 
billion in november and 63 billion in october 
outflows for the full year were the largest on record the last 
big outflow 254 billion occurred in 1981 when interest rates 
for competing moneymarket mutual funds skyrocketed above 20 
percent at a time when thrift rates were capped by law 
total deposits with interest credited declined 16 billion in 
1989 to 946 billion 
what youre seeing now is unprecedented but its not 
surprising said economist martin regalia of the national council 
of savings institutions 
early in the year the industry lost deposits in part because 
sampl problems had shaken customers confidence but economists say 
the shrinkage in the last half of the year is almost entirely a 
response to tough financial standards in the sampl bailout 
legislation enacted in august 
the rules require thrifts to back their loans with more of their 
owners money most cant raise the capital and as a result must 
trim their balance sheets 
thrifts shed 256 billion in assets in december with 46 
billion of that coming at sampls under government control and almost 
threefourths of the remainder at weakly capitalized thrifts still 
operating independently 
sampl assets at the end of the year totaled 125 trillion down 
100 billion or 73 percent from a year earlier in contrast 
commercial bank assets grew 54 percent to 33 trillion 
i think the sampl downsizing is going to continue throughout 
1990 and maybe into 1991 as well although we might see some ebbing 
of the pace regalia said 
