inflation speeded up in the united states and 
other major industrial countries in 1989 for the third year in a 
row the international monetary fund reported wednesday 
prices paid by consumers in the seven industrial countries rose 
an average of 44 percent compared with 34 percent in 1988 3 
percent in 1987 and 24 percent in 1986 
the fund calculated prices in the united states increased their 
rise from 19 percent in 1986 to 48 percent last year 
the fund said last years overall increase last year was 
relatively moderate compared with the average annual increase of 
about 79 percent registered during the period 197085 
britain showed the biggest rise to 78 percent from 34 
percent three years earlier according to the report in the funds 
monthly imf memorandum 
the increase was also high in italy although complete figures 
were not in by last august italy was showing a 63 percent annual 
inflation rate compared with 51 percent for 1988 
japan which had only a 06 percent inflation rate in 1986 
showed the smallest increase in 1989 at 23 percent west germany 
had a 28 percent inflation rate last year the fund said 
prices in france increased 35 percent in 1989 and canada had a 
52 annual inflation rate through november the last month for 
which the fund had figures 
the fund reported a continued rapid rise in prices for consumers 
in third world countries though only partial figures for 1989 were 
available 
it reported an average annual rate of 898 percent for 130 
countries in august 1989 compared with 587 percent in 1988 and 
267 percent in 1986 
the western hemisphere where figures were available for the 
entire year led the third world with an average increase of 3346 
percent far more than the annual rate of 824 percent in 1986 
prices in developing nations in the western hemisphere have 
risen 11677 percent since 1985 the fund said 
that rise was heavily influenced by rates by brazil which 
accounts for a third of latin americas economy prices paid by 
brazilians rose 1287 percent in 1989 after inflation of 682 
percent in 1988 
argentinas inflation was even faster reaching an annual rate 
of 3967 percent last august 
developing countries in asia were much more successful in 
holding down prices south korean prices rose 57 percent last 
year less than the year before most asian countries appeared able 
to keep inflation in single digits though the fund had no figure 
to show what happened after china reported 207 percent in 1988 
