<TEXT>
jacqueline onassis agreed wednesday to 
give a group of wampanoag indians a plot of land and 100000 in 
exchange for a tiny beachfront site ending an acrimonious 10year 
dispute over the property 
the case pitted mrs onassis desire for privacy against the 
indians belief that they should retain tribal lands on marthas 
vineyard 
after all this time im just happy the land was settled 
said selma weissberg one of the 25 descendants of william 
vanderhoop a wampanoag who lived in the area in the 1870s and 
owned the 15acre plot ive lived on the island all my life and 
im happy that we have some of our land back 
the agreement was ratified by judge john s macdougall jr in 
dukes county probate court 
at issue was a 15acre section of land surrounded by onassis 
estate but owned primarily by the wampanoags a tribe that has 
lived at the picturesque cliffs of gay head for centuries 
the tribe considers the land sacred the wampanoags believe the 
tract is the last resting place of the great chief moshup and his 
wife squant tribal lore holds it was there that moshup threw his 
children into the sea when he foresaw the coming of the white man 
the new plot of land is about two acres with a 250foot ocean 
frontage at zacks cliff in gay head 
in 1980 mrs onassis obtained onesixth interest in the 
15acre plot and sought to buy the remaining fivesixths from the 
25 descendants of vanderhoop she wanted to close access to the 
parcel and keep beachgoers and tourists away from her 400acre 
property 
but the wampanoags resisted and a series of lawsuits and 
countersuits followed 
according to the terms of the agreement signed wednesday the 
wampanoags will surrender title and access to the 15acre site in 
exchange for 100000 and the larger section of beachfront 1500 
feet closer to the nearest road mrs onassis also will pay all 
costs related to the land transfer and the indians agreed to drop 
all suits pending in the matter 
this way everybody wins said attorney paul sulla who 
represented the wampanoags until now theyve always been asked 
to move from their land and given money now theyve gotten some 
land in exchange 
brian hurley one of mrs onassis attorneys said shes just 
pleased to have resolved this long matter and hopes to continue 
being good neighbors she wants to put it behind her 
since 1974 various wampanoags have regained about 400 acres of 
what they consider tribal land on marthas vineyard through a 
series of federal lawsuits 
they claimed that the 1790 indian nonintercourse act which 
forbids transfer of indian lands without federal approval was 
violated in the 1870s when the state redistributed tribal lands to 
other island residents 
the wampanoags have maintained a tribal structure for more than 
370 years according to tribal council president donald widdiss 
but they did not receive federal recognition until 1987 there are 
only 250 wampanoags left at gay head and only 630 total in the 
nation 
