<TEXT>
an australian scientist who sees divine values 
in nature and a hindu lawyer who started communities for lepers in 
india were named wednesday as cowinners of the 1990 templeton 
prize for progress in religion 
the 580000 prize the largest in any field went to 
biologistgeneticist charles k birch of sydney and murlidhar 
devidas amte who established five centers for lepers in the area 
of nagpur india 
the prize was founded in 1972 by financier john templeton a 
presbyterian who keeps the amount higher than the nobel prizes in 
the belief that religion is more important an international panel 
of judges picks the winners 
templeton urged more research into spiritual realities when he 
named the winners at the church center for the united nations 
the accelerating discovery rate in natural sciences needs to 
be matched by mans spiritual progress and discovery he said 
much evidence has been found that gods ongoing creative process 
is accelerating 
the prize winners reflected two aspects of religion its 
intellectual ramifications in science and its altruistic impulse in 
serving the weak 
birch 71 a university of sydney biologist from 1960 until his 
recent retirement and veteran of sciencereligion conferences 
maintains that the interrelationship of nature humanity and god 
finds support in physics 
he wrote that this has been emphasized by the ecological crisis 
which has shown the negative results of a mere mechanistic view of 
nature all actual entities have an inner reality as well as an 
outer reality birch said 
for example he said nothing will save the whales unless 
we attribute to whales intrinsic value in themselves and to god 
birch who has been a research fellow at several us 
universities was cited for his reconciliation of the biological 
and the religious understanding of creation 
amte 75 is called baba or father by colleagues and 
patients his largest leper center covering 450 acres accommodates 
1400 lepers and includes a cottage hospital library cooperative 
shops bank workshops training schools theaters homes for aged 
and infirm lepers and technical college with 7500 students 
amte was born into a wealthy brahmin family educated at a 
christian college and became an attorney but rebelled against 
caste barriers to help untouchables set up cooperatives and unions 
an experience resembling that of st francis initially turned 
amte to serving lepers he said he was so repelled at his first 
encounter with one that he fled then returned to befriend him 
amte like his friend the late mahatma gandhi extolled the 
example of christ but remained a hindu 
everyone should attempt to walk in the shadow of the cross 
he wrote that means you are in the company of that life which 
scuttled itself to save others 
australias un ambassador peter wialenski and indias cr 
gharekan attended the news conference with several religious and 
public leaders 
the prize is to be presented may 8 in london 
templeton said the prize is intended to help people see the 
infinity of ways god acts in the world and reveals himself to 
different cultures adding exciting new advances are being made 
in every religion 
noting that millions are spent annually for research in natural 
sciences he said similar manpower and resources devoted to 
research in spiritual subjects could lead to greater blessings for 
mankind 
previous winners of the prize include mother teresa of calcutta 
evangelist billy graham science philosopher thomas torrance of 
scotland and russian exile writer alexander solzhenitsyn 
