<TEXT>
a bipartisan panel called for flexible 
spending limits on congressional campaigns wednesday but did not 
address many of the alleged abuses that have put the issue on the 
front burner in congress 
the panel of experts sided with democrats to support a voluntary 
spending ceiling with discount tv and mail rates as an incentive 
for compliance 
but it rejected democratic calls for public financing and 
instead endorsed republican desires to limit corporate and labor 
political action committees or pacs 
gop desires to loosen rules on indiviudal contributions to 
reduce a perceived advantage by incumbents and to make the 
political parties the engine for raising and spending funds also 
won the panels endorsement 
senate democratic leader george mitchell of maine hailed the 
panels 41page report as breakthrough recommendations for 
untangling a bitterly partisan struggle 
senate republican leader bob dole of kansas called it a 
potential breakthrough saying the panel of six experts three 
each picked by dole and mitchell at least touched on some of 
the hot buttons 
democrats nonetheless planned to push through the senate rules 
committee on thursday their version of a bill that has both 
spending caps and provisions for taxpayer financing 
mitchell acknowledged that the bill he is cosponsoring with 
sens david boren dokla and robert c byrd dwva has no 
chance to get past a presidential veto but he said it provides a 
vehicle for negotiations between the parties 
meanwhile rep beryl anthony of arkansas chairman of the 
democratic congressional campaign committee said house democrats 
are nearing completion of a bill that would set a voluntary ceiling 
of 550000 on what a house candidate could spend democrats 
previously had wanted a 400000 ceiling 
the task force called for reasonably high and flexible 
voluntary spending ceilings reflecting the extra costs of running 
in states where advertising in adjacent highcost media markets is 
required but it would not count limited contribtions by instate 
residents to instate candidates 
the panel ignored many issues raised by the savings and loan 
crisis 
for example it did not touch socalled leadership political 
action committees or pacs pacs run by members 
it also had no recommendation on taxexempt foundations of the 
13 million that phoenix sampl operator charles h keating jr 
contributed to five senate candidates 850000 was through a 
taxexempt voter registration foundation headed by the son of sen 
alan cranston dcalif 
the panel called for prohibtions on the bundling or 
gathering of many contributions by business and labor pacs but 
endorsed as little obvious cause for concern such activities by 
individuals 
keating whose failed sampl may cost the taxpayers 2 billion 
bundled more than 200000 in individual contributions from members 
of his family and business associates for the reelection campaigns 
of the five senators 
the five sens john mccain rariz dennis deconcini 
dariz john glenn dohio donald w riegle dmich and 
cranston are now under investigation by the senate ethics 
committee for interceding with regulators on behalf of keatings 
lincoln savings and loan association 
recommendations by the task force include 
giving parties authority to raise and spend unlimited amounts 
on voter registration drives phone banks getoutthevote 
campaigns and direct mail 
raising the 25000 limit an individual can make to a party 
committee 
providing a 100 percent tax credit up to a specified amount 
for any indivual who contributes to a candidate in the 
contributors state 
a modest increase in the current 1000 limit an individual 
can contribute to one candidate and the 25000 ceiling on all 
contributions by an individual 
reducing from 5000 to 2500 the contribution pacs can make 
to a candidate for each of the primary and general elections but 
only after total pac contributions reach onethird of the 
candidates spending limit 
prohibiting pacs from making postelection contributions for 
two years after an election to reduce a candidates campaign debt 
requiring radio and television stations to provide eight hours 
of free time each year to candidates parties would allocate the 
time 
