<TEXT>
lithuanias parliament will meet this weekend to 
declare independence from the soviet union activists in the baltic 
republic said wednesday 
sweeping victories in recent elections have given backers of 
sajudis the proindependence popular movement dominance in the 
lithuanian parliament and sajudis leaders have decided to force 
the issue of secession activist audris siaurusavicius said 
vilnius radio reported that lithuanian president algirdas 
brazauskas met with president mikhail s gorbachev on monday to 
discuss secession and was presented with a bill for 34 billion 
that the republic supposedly owes the soviet union for resources 
invested there 
but lithuania has not presented its bill yet to the soviet 
union for losses incurred by 50 years of soviet rule 
siaurusavicius said 
brazauskas speaking wednesday night on lithuanian television 
said there was no need to frighten ourselves and others about 
the economic consequences of secession he said the republic would 
be so much better off on its own that the advantages would offset 
its debt to moscow according to eduardas potashinskas another 
sajudis activist 
according to a draft law currently under consideration in the 
soviet legislature a republic that wants to secede faces a series 
of lengthy procedures including a fiveyear coolingoff period and 
required approval from the 2250member congress of peoples 
deputies 
the soviet constitution guarantees republics the right to 
secede but the procedure has not been spelled out in soviet law 
the parliament is sure to come out with some form of 
declaration of independence when it meets sunday said 
potashinskas an editor at lithuanian tv in a telephone interview 
from vilnius lithuanias capital 
prosecession sentiment in lithuania has been swelling for 
months but sajudis decided to move now to preempt gorbachevs 
plans for a vastly more powerful presidency with the right to crack 
down on restive republics the national congress is to meet monday 
to consider the presidency proposal 
why so fast i think gorbachev himself created such a 
reaction said siaurusavicius a reporter for rebirth the 
sajudis newspaper if there were no such proposal on the 
presidency we wouldnt have done this now 
gorbachev has repeatedly denounced separatists and asked 
activists to give moscow time to work out the terms of a new soviet 
federation before moving to secede 
the lithuanian supreme soviet will meet saturday night to settle 
procedural questions and address independence on sunday said 
siaurusavicius 
siaurusavicius said it was not clear what changes would 
immediately follow the declaration we just have to say it this 
is not secession but its saying they must end their annexation 
they should leave 
all three baltic republics latvia lithuania and estonia were 
independent nations between the two world wars they were annexed 
by the soviet union in 1940 while under occupation by the red army 
siaurusavicius said sajudis leaders were expecting moscows 
response to the declaration of independence to be restrained and 
did not anticipate use of force but he said the republic of 37 
million people could already feel the effects of a mounting soviet 
economic blockade with many factories hurting for raw materials 
and expecting the pinch to get worse 
he predicted the soviet union would probably not be among the 
first to respond to lithuanias planned appeal to the countries of 
the world to recognize it as a fullfledged sovereign state 
the declaration will technically be merely a reconfirmation of 
lithuanias declaration of independence in 1918 siaurusavicius 
said 
last month the lithuanian parliament passed a measure declaring 
as unlawful and invalid the 1940 act that incorporated the 
republic into the soviet union it called for talks with the 
kremlin on restoring lithuanian independence 
an article in the government newspaper izvestia on wednesday 
complained that lithuania is getting public opinion used to the 
fact that it is leaving without thinking through the economic 
and political difficulties secession will create 
god can we really imagine what pain suffering clashes and 
insults this break threatens wrote l kapeliushny izvestias 
correspondent in vilnius 
he listed among expected problems trade imbalances the 
difficulty of deciding what to do about various sovietbuilt 
factories and the fate of lithuanian residents who want to retain 
their soviet citizenship 
about half the soviet unions 15 republics now have popular 
groups pushing for independence or greater sovereignty including 
moldavia georgia armenia azerbaijan estonia and latvia 
