<TEXT>
roman catholics still believe confession is good 
for the soul but many disagree with their bishops on whether the 
sacrament of penance is a necessary way to reach reconciliation 
with god 
in a survey of bishops and parishioners the church hierarchy 
said the loss of a sense of sin was the top reason for smaller 
lines at church confessionals while the first reason listed by 
laity was that reconciliation was being experienced by other means 
including the sacrament of holy communion 
the differing perspectives were so great that a less pervasive 
sense of sin was only seventh on the laitys list of reasons 
catholics are going to confession less frequently while the idea 
reconciliation is experienced by other means was fifth on the 
bishops list 
for better and worse the sons and daughters of european 
immigrant catholics who once filled confessionals each week have 
become part of the american mainstream said the rev michael j 
walsh executive director of the secretariat for pastoral research 
and practices of the us catholic conference 
what has happened with western culture in general is that the 
anchor in the judeochristian culture has been loosened by 
secularization walsh said 
the study undertaken by the committee for pastoral research and 
practices of the national conference of catholic bishops surveyed 
2500 priests 2850 active lay catholics and about 380 bishops in 
the spring and summer of 1988 the majority of catholics surveyed 
55 percent said they went to confession once or twice a year four 
percent said they went once a week 5 percent said they went 
monthly and 17 percent said every two or three months nineteen 
percent said they never celebrated the sacrament an average of 18 
hours a week is scheduled for confessions in parishes 
the bishops attributed the decline in confessions to a less 
pervasive sense of sin confusion about what is morally right and 
wrong and disagreement with the churchs moral teaching 
the report of the committee on pastoral practices said the 
individualism and religious pluralism in american culture have 
taken a toll on catholics many of whom are no longer willing to 
submit to the claims on human freedom posed by god and others 
while pluralism encourages a perspective that all systems are 
equally valid the bishops committee said its most practical 
consequence however is the creation of an environment of total 
relativism 
the naming confronting repenting and confessing of ones 
sins is never easy amid the cacophony of moral claims it becomes 
even more difficult the committee said 
the issue was viewed differently from the pew with lay 
catholics saying they are experiencing forgiveness by other means 
than confession 
the part that surprised me was the comfortableness with which 
people find reconciliation by other means said bishop john j 
mcraith of the diocese of owensboro ky 
more than 80 percent of the lay respondents said they 
experienced reconciliation by receiving the eucharist other ways 
catholics reported experiencing forgiveness were by personal 
prayer making an act of contrition talking with a friend doing 
charitable works and reading the bible 
the priests surveyed were divided on the issue saying general 
confusion over what is right and wrong and the fact laypeople are 
experiencing forgiveness by other means were the two main reasons 
for the drop in confessions they also said an excessive sense of 
guilt motivated many confessions in the past 
the good news in the survey the bishops committee said was 
that although catholics are going to confession less often the 
quality of those sacramental encounters has improved 
bishops priests and laity all expressed particular satisfaction 
with penance services during which individual confessions are heard 
as part of a liturgical celebration 
people were pleased with the forms of communal penance 
service mcraith said the emphasis was placed on the quality 
of the celebration of the sacrament 
for their part priests requested greater training for their 
role as confessors particularly with regard to the new 
possibilities for moral and spiritual dialogue created by the 
revised rites of penance which offer the option of facetoface 
confessions 
the bishops committee recommended that dioceses give priority 
to training priests and seminarians as confessors 
the committees recommendations for increasing interest in the 
sacrament of penance also included not limiting penance services to 
advent and lent and considering offering confessions at more 
convenient times such as before mass 
confession needs to be different from what it was years 
ago mcraith said 
</TEXT>
