<TEXT>
the sight of iron mike tyson on the canvas 
and drexel burnham lambert similarly flattened has prompted the 
pundits to proclaim the end of an era the end of the 80s of 
excess 
from the separated trumps to contaminated perrier the evidence 
seems to be all around us 
shearson lehman hutton junk bonds the dow jones average the 
hunt brothers kohlberg kravis rjr nabisco it just seems like 
everyone and everything that used to be riding high are sinking 
fast 
as a matter of fact the sound of the mighty falling is getting 
pretty distracting 
like iron mike they mostly all complain they didnt see it 
coming 
worse the experts herald the end of modern gluttony as we know 
it noting the obvious coincidence of the opening of a new decade 
but these sudden shifts as cataclysmic as they might seem to 
30something eyes are really not the end of anything they might 
be more accurately described as reruns of a very old show which 
aside from titillation provide fresh lessons in a law as undeniable 
as gravity 
since midas perhaps since adam the consequences of risky 
business have been spurned to the peril of those who dare to pursue 
happiness a little too voraciously 
in the vernacular the chickens always come home to roost 
what goes around comes around again and again and again 
anyone who doubts these fundamentals need only look as far as 
the next headline new coke is coming around again for heavens 
sake 
what is so surprising about all these earthshattering events is 
not their occurrence but our reaction our jaws drop at the news 
that tysons brow has been busted by a fellow named douglas and 
that drexel has met a bankruptcycourt fate worse than rudolph 
giuliani 
what is all the fuss about hasnt it always been true that the 
bigger they are the harder they fall 
the case could generally be made could it not that flabbiness 
breeds carelessness whether were talking about prizefighters or 
junkbond underwriters 
yet even those who are 40something 50something 60something 
and beyond seem awestruck by recent events that includes a lot of 
people who saw gene tunney upset jack dempsey and glasssteagall 
break up the morgan dynasty on wall street 
maybe our hearts are leading us astray with the endless 
economic expansion and the fall of communism its hard to imagine 
a war we cant win today 
but the road of american history is littered with blown tires 
if youve read the account of the rjr nabisco fight barbarians 
at the gate by reporters bryan burrough and john helyar move on 
to an even fatter tome now heading for the bookstores called the 
house of morgan by ron chernow 
the reading experience will provide ample proof that henry 
kravis peter cohen and michael milken were not the first 
barbarians to crash wall streets gates the morgan empire grew 
into such a financial behemoth that congress was inspired to 
legislate against it and erect a legal wall between the banking and 
securities businesses so was born the glasssteagall act of 1933 
a little more than half a century later after gargantuan merger 
fees pushed the pendulum all the way back in favor of brokerage 
houses lawmakers began to mull the repeal of glasssteagall 
when they say it just cant happen the champ is invincible the 
deal is airtight or the business is too big to fail think about 
all those previously vanquished barbarians 
the talent for making the same mistake much more than once is 
peculiarly american from celebrity to captain of industry we love 
to demonstrate just how easy it is to abuse the secrets of our 
success 
