their currency is named for the sun but with 
inflation of nearly 3000 percent last year peruvians got little 
warmth from it 
the first truck i bought 15 years ago cost me 10 million 
soles now that wont even buy me a pack of cigarettes said 
miguel guzman who owns a trucking company in lima 
guzman quoted prices in the old currency the sol spanish for 
sun 
in 1986 when the sol had fallen to 14000 to the dollar the 
government lopped off three zeros and renamed it the inti sun in 
quechua the indian language spoken by nearly half the population 
four years later a dollar buys 14000 intis which means it 
would buy 14 million soles if they were still around 
to peruvians like nearly everyone else jokes are spiritual 
life preservers against disaster the latest one in lima is that 
the government will chop off three zeros again and call its money 
the lupaca sun in aymara perus second major indian language 
the inflation rate for the past year which meant prices ended 
the year 30 times higher on average than 12 months earlier was 
surpassed only by argentinas 4924 percent 
doris mandujano 27 one of three daughters in a workingclass 
family of 16 including grandchildren says the last year has 
brought fundamental changes in the way they live 
sometimes at dinner there isnt enough food to go around 
she said we used to have milk and marmalade for breakfast now 
its bread and oatmeal weve given up trying to provide clothing 
and medicine for everyone 
her family is squeezed into a threebedroom cementblock house 
miss mandujanos father built in villa el salvador a shantytown on 
the outskirts of lima 
miss mandujanos parents and seven of the children including 
herself have jobs and contribute to meeting the familys needs 
she has the additional job of trying to make and follow a budget 
our pay doesnt keep up with prices she said sometimes 
by the fourth day of the month weve already spent what was 
budgeted for two weeks and so the crisis begins 
most economists blame government policies that favored 
consumption over production while creating a huge deficit that fed 
inflation 
they say populist president alan garcias administration has 
subsidized basic goods and services to the point of bankrupting the 
very state companies that provide the services 
a gallon of gasoline costs the equivalent of only 40 cents but 
the state oil company petroperu is on the verge of bankruptcy 
electricity and water are among the worlds cheapest but both 
are rationed to limas 7 milliion people largely because of the 
dilapidated systems some parts of the city have been without water 
for weeks 
ernesto amans president of the state water company said nearly 
half the water leaving treatment plants was lost through leaking 
underground mains and the company could not afford the 18 million 
needed for repairs 
while subsidized prices remain low food and clothing rose more 
than 2500 percent last year entertainment soared more than 10000 
percent and education nearly 20000 percent according to official 
statistics 
