<DOCNO> AP900307-0223 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
nearly two years after the roof ripped off an 
aging boeing 737 jetliner over hawaii the government is imposing 
the first set of partsreplacement rules for older planes 
at the same time the federal aviation administration announced 
plans worked out with the aviation industry to require a detailed 
cycle of inspections for corrosion in boeing airliners 
the final rules announced tuesday are aimed at correcting 
metalfatigue problems in airliners that have gone through 
thousands of takeoffs and landings they require replacements of 
parts and will cost airlines an estimated 142 million over the 
next four years 
the anticorrosion measures are estimated to cost 38720 for 
each boeing 737 over the sixyear inspection cycle 80000 for 
each boeing 727 80640 for each boeing 707 and 188800 for each 
boeing 747 
foreign regulatory agencies generally follow faa requirements 
for usbuilt planes 
the rules come as no surprise to the industry which set up the 
task force that proposed them 
the aging airliner effort was started after the roof of an aloha 
airlines 737 ripped off at 24000 feet over maui hawaii in april 
1988 a flight attendant was swept to her death and 64 passengers 
were injured the plane was 19 years old and had made nearly 90000 
flights 
the accident was caused primarily by metal fatigue but 
corrosion also was found the faa said 
the new fatigue rules which take effect in 30 days give 
airlines four years to comply with all the requirements and will 
immediately affect 115 older usregistered boeing aircraft 
tony broderick faa regulations chief said the agency believes 
that if the regulations are followed there will be no need to 
retire airliners at a given age 
final fatigue rules for mcdonnell douglas airliners are to be 
issued in a couple of months with rules for other airliners to be 
issued before the end of the year broderick said 
corrosion rules also will be proposed for other jetliners he 
said and will become final after airlines have an opportunity to 
comment 
broderick said that although most airlines have programs to 
detect and repair corrosion the proposed rules would impose 
detailed faa requirements for inspections of 19 specific areas of 
each airliner 
under the proposal inspections would have to be performed most 
often under lavatories and galleys where corrosive liquids might 
collect and in wheel wells 
broderick said the program could pose a relatively big 
burden on some small airlines but that if carriers find 
themselves overburdened it probably means they have not been 
conducting adequate corrosion inspections on their own 
the goal is for each airline to set up a program that will find 
only harmless corrosion that can be corrected quickly with each 
inspection 
more serious corrosion which would require repair or 
replacement of parts or which might endanger the safety of the 
airliner would have to be reported to the manufacturer 
the faa has based its rules on boeing service bulletins and the 
experiences of domestic and foreign airliners that participated in 
the task force 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

