<DOCNO> AP900307-0225 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the united states has 70 percent of the 
worlds computer software market but could lose its lead without 
better legal protection as other countries develop their software 
a congressional study says 
with continued innovation the united states can keep outshining 
its foreign competitors the congressional office of technology 
assessment said in a study released today 
it said intellectual property protection encourages innovation 
by providing incentives for creation and security for investors 
last year software and related services were a 60 billion 
industry in the united states software refers to sets of 
instructions for computers whether they are stored in punched 
cards magnetic tape disks or on chips the term can encompass 
data as well as programs 
mitchell d kapor the creator of lotus 123 told a house 
subcommittee that overprotection of software is as pernicious as 
underprotection in its stifling effects on innovation 
he said his industry has made an unsteady but stubborn march 
to extend copyright protection of computer software but he said 
it is possible to go too far 
i honestly believe that this industry isnt mature enough to 
cope with a barrage of new laws kapor said congress could 
help both the software industry and its customers if when it 
passes laws their legislative histories tell the courts that when 
they consider a copyright case they should err on the side of 
innovation over protection 
the software publishers association a worldwide trade 
association representing 575 microcomputer software developers and 
publishers said in a statement that patent protection for their 
product is not universally endorsed partly because publishers are 
concerned that the governments patent and trademark office cant 
adequately review applications 
publishers believe that the pto is understaffed underfunded 
and so is not equipped to evaluate most software patent 
applications in a timely and effective fashion the association 
said 
there is fear of foreign competition especially from the 
japanese who reportedly plan to spend 125 billion over 10 years 
for programming research and development especially in the field 
of artificial intelligence where the goal is to make computers 
think more like humans 
the congressional study said there are basic questions about 
providing too much as well as too little legal protection for 
software 
new technologies have long challenged existing protections but 
usually accommodations are made 
for instance the first copyright statute dealt only with 
maps charts and books but copyright has been able to deal with 
hard questions posed by works like engravings musical 
compositions photographs the study said 
with software however the items needing protection are not 
clear 
as writing and checking lines of program instructions 
socalled code becomes more automated some software producers 
want to protect the logic and idea of a program not just the 
effort required to write the code and check it others worry that 
computeraided software development will make copying easier to 
disguise 
the study says drawing the line between derivative works and new 
creations and determining authorship is likely to become more 
difficult 
but it also points out that lawyers and many in the software 
industry believe existing copyrights and patents adequately protect 
software 
at the same time that some are calling for major revisions in 
software protection says the study others are arguing that 
the current system is not broken and does not need fixing or at 
least can be finetuned within the existing framework 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

