<DOCNO> AP900307-0231 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when the time comes for doling out financial 
encouragement and moral support dinks often must wait at the end 
of the line 
the millions of modern american households nicknamed for their 
doubleincome nokids status are widely presumed to be doing just 
fine on their own with economic advantages few others enjoy 
social commentators have gone so far as to portray dinks as 
egomaniacs hooked on instant gratification if a layoff or other 
reversal hits either half of a dink partnership sympathy may be 
slow in coming even from close friends and relatives 
the accuracy of such generalizations of course varies widely 
from one twoincome zerodependent living unit to the next 
even in households where the cash flow never seems to stop say 
experts in matters of personal finance dinks face problems of 
money management and planning that are just about unique to their 
species 
while two incomes can give couples a financial edge that edge 
is often blunted by poor planning says candace e trunzo in her 
book financial planning for the twocareer family recently 
published under the auspices of john hancock financial services 
not only financial stability but family stability can suffer 
if there is no management or compromise in a twocareer family 
the steady flow of multiple paychecks in a dink household can 
overcome any impulse to develop disciplined habits or plan for the 
future making such regimens harder and harder to adopt and adjust 
to with the passage of time 
if a twocareer family has something of a cushion against a 
disruption in the life of either worker it also may be doubly 
exposed to the risk of changing economic circumstances 
with such considerations in mind many advisers urge dinks to 
save a greater percentage of their income than others might deem 
prudent as much as 25 percent or even more 
sock it away before you spend it on restaurants clothes and 
cars says john erb at the accounting firm of deloitte amp touche 
societys presumption that dinks are more capable than most of 
bearing the cost of government shows up clearly in the tax code 
because they lack most of the deductions that reduce taxable 
income they stand virtually defenseless before the tax man erb 
observes 
to reduce the tax bite erb recommends that dinks make the 
maximum contributions possible to such things as individual 
retirement accounts and employersponsored retirement savings 
programs 
he also suggests that when they save they give extra emphasis 
to growth investments such as stocks and mutual funds seeking out 
longterm capital gains over current income from their nest eggs 
tax rates are now the same for both capital gains and dividend 
and interest income but tax bills on capital gains dont arise 
until you decide to sell an investment 
for unmarried dinks planning is complicated by questions of 
what rights lawmakers the courts and society are willing to accord 
them for example on the death of either partner in the household 
married couples are urged to consider special strategies as 
well for instance they may be prime candidates to save on tax 
deductions for medical or miscellaneous expenses by filing their 
returns separately rather than jointly 
advisers also suggest that twocareer families give their 
employee benefit programs close scrutiny to eliminate overlaps 
when it comes to things like insurance trunzo writes the goal 
is to be adequately but not overly insured particularly if you 
are paying for benefits from your own pockets 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

