the nations big three automakers are reviewing 
their estimates for 1990 sales amid signs that sales early this 
year have been stronger than they had expected 
i think that as the year begins to unfold that the more 
optimistic forecast of more like 145 million cars and trucks is 
more likely chrysler corp vice chairman gerald greenwald said 
in an interview tuesday 
late last year chrysler was the most pessimistic of the big 
three companies forecasting car and truck sales industrywide of 
142 million for 1990 down from 1485 million in 1989 
backing up three months as the fourth quarter of last year 
unfolded there was a lot of concern that this year could really be 
tough greenwald said 
since then chrysler and general motors corp have delayed 
factory shutdowns and layoffs january and february sales were 
running less than 1 percent behind last years rate and the spring 
buying season is getting under way 
on monday when february sales figures were reported robert 
rewey ford motor cos north american sales vice president 
indicated that the no 2 automaker may revise its estimate 
looking at the first two months of the new year sales are not 
only much improved from the fourth quarter but somewhat ahead of 
