<TEXT>
japans nec corp and american telephone amp 
telegraph co said wednesday they would cooperate in developing and 
making a wide range of semiconductors and other computer 
technologies 
the agreement should enhance the us companys access to 
japans worlddominating electronics market 
nec the worlds largest maker of semiconductors agreed to 
cooperate with atampts microelectronics division on various projects 
for at least five years 
under the agreement atampt microelectronics will receive a 
license to market design and produce necs advanced gatearray 
computer chips which are used widely in computers and other 
electronics devices 
atampt did not have the technology to produce these chips on its 
own spokeswoman barbara baklarz said from atampt microelectronics 
headquarters in berkeley heights nj 
an important feature of this agreement is that customers of 
both companies will enjoy the advantage of having two stable 
sources of identical gatearray products william warwick 
president of atampt microelectronics told reporters in tokyo 
in return nec will receive atampts most sophisticated 
computeraided tools used to design computer chips warwick said 
he said the two companies also are working on accelerating the 
placement of atampt semiconductor products into a variety of nec 
products such as communications systems and computers 
in addition atampt microelectronics will help manufacture certain 
nec chips widely used in consumer electronics products 
this will allow japanese customers to obtain products made by 
an american firm and will give atampt a greater presence in the 
japanese market especially with consumer electronics companies 
warwick said 
this agreement shows that one single company cannot stand 
alone and needs more resources to survive said tomohir 
matsumura an nec executive vice president and director of its 
semiconductor division 
it makes sense for atampt as a big semiconductor user to go to 
nec a big semiconductor producer said charles elliott an 
electronics analyst with the investment firm goldman sachs amp co 
but atampt is also a big semiconductor developer and it makes 
sense for atampt to design and nec to produce 
millard phelps an analyst with the san francisco brokerage 
hambrecht amp quist inc said the agreement is part of a global 
cooperation trend among electronics companies 
atampt microelectronics announced two weeks ago that it will 
produce semiconductor memory chips for the international market in 
a joint venture with mitsubishi electric corp another major 
japanese chip manufacturer 
international business machines corp said in january that it 
would set up a joint venture with siemens ag of west germany to 
develop advanced memory chips 
neither atampt nor nec would attach monetary figures to the 
accord but warwick said he was confident it would be continued 
after five years 
gatearray chips are the logic chips that customize computers 
according to their use they are a key component of a computer 
along with its microprocessor or brain and its memory 
atampt lacked the technology to produce complementary metal oxide 
semiconductor or cmos gatearray chips ms baklarz said these 
are considered the most advanced gatearray chips 
the agreement also will aid necs policy of increasing purchases 
of foreign semiconductors to ease trade friction 
us officials angered by what they claim is a closed japanese 
market to foreign semiconductors say japan agreed to boost the 
foreign share of the semiconductor market here to 20 percent by 
july 1991 
but foreign chips share stood at only 129 percent in the final 
quarter of 1989 according to the ministry of international trade 
and industry 
nec expects to purchase 53 million worth of atampt 
semiconductors in 1990 and more in 1991 though there is no target 
figure for next year nec spokeswoman akiko sato said 
the manufacturer plans to raise its internal use of foreign 
computer chips from the current 20 percent to 23 percent by july 
1991 when the usjapan semiconductor accord expires and to 
about 24 percent by the end of next year miss sato said 
</TEXT>
