<TEXT>
the farm credit system reported wednesday that 
its fourthquarter profit fell 33 percent from a year earlier 
the system said it earned 181 million in the three months ended 
dec 31 down from 270 million in the fourth quarter of 1989 
the decline in net income was due largely to a reduction in 
provisions for loan losses reflecting an improvement in credit 
quality said daniel bienz a vice president of the federal farm 
credit banks funding corp the financing arm of the farm credit 
system 
he said net interest income rose while most expenses remained 
stable pershare figures do not apply 
the farm credit system is a nationwide system of federally 
chartered agricultural lending institutions serving the rural 
economy and cooperatively owned by their borrowers 
the system took several steps last year to streamline its 
structure following 1987 legislation that included the issuance of 
up to 4 billion in governmentbacked lowinterest loans 
for all of 1989 the system earned 695 million down from 704 
million the previous year 
for the second consecutive year the system has achieved 
favorable results suggesting continued progress in returning to 
financial soundness and strength said james a brickley 
president and chief executive officer of the federal farm credit 
banks funding corp 
net interest income totaled 275 million for the fourth quarter 
up from 216 million in the yearearlier quarter and 101 billion 
for the full year up from 787 million in 1988 
the system said net interest income increased as a result of 
continued improvement in the credit quality of its loan portfolio 
stemming from a reduction in nonaccrual loans 
when loans are placed on nonaccrual status they are accounted 
for only as they come in rather than when they are due 
